<!-- HERO -->
<div class="hero">
  <div class="hero-badge">Updated April 2026</div>
  <h1>NVC Processing Time 2026:<br>How Long Does Each Stage Take?</h1>
  <p>After USCIS approves your immigrant visa petition, your case lands at the National Visa Center. Here's exactly what happens — and how long each step takes in 2026.</p>

  <div class="timeline-bar">
    <div class="tbar-step">
      <div class="tbar-label">USCIS → NVC Transfer</div>
      <div class="tbar-time">2–6 wks</div>
      <div class="tbar-name">Case initiated</div>
    </div>
    <div class="tbar-step">
      <div class="tbar-label">Fee Invoice</div>
      <div class="tbar-time">2–6 wks</div>
      <div class="tbar-name">Pay fees</div>
    </div>
    <div class="tbar-step">
      <div class="tbar-label">Document Review</div>
      <div class="tbar-time">4–12 wks</div>
      <div class="tbar-name">Submit docs</div>
    </div>
    <div class="tbar-step">
      <div class="tbar-label">Interview Scheduled</div>
      <div class="tbar-time">2–6 wks</div>
      <div class="tbar-name">Case complete</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="content-wrap">
  <div class="main-col">

    <h2 id="what-is-nvc">What Is the NVC and What Does It Do?</h2>
    <p>The <strong>National Visa Center (NVC)</strong> is a U.S. Department of State processing facility in Portsmouth, New Hampshire. It acts as the bridge between USCIS (which approves petitions) and U.S. embassies abroad (which issue visas).</p>
    <p>The NVC's job is to:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Receive your approved I-130 or I-129F from USCIS</li>
      <li>Collect visa fees from both the petitioner and beneficiary</li>
      <li>Review all supporting documents for completeness</li>
      <li>Run a preliminary eligibility check before the embassy interview</li>
      <li>Schedule the immigrant visa interview at the appropriate U.S. embassy or consulate</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Only <strong>immigrant visas</strong> (CR-1, IR-1, family preference) go through NVC. The K-1 fiancé visa skips NVC entirely — it goes directly from USCIS to the embassy.</p>

    <h2 id="stages">Stage-by-Stage NVC Timeline (2026)</h2>

    <div class="stage-grid">
      <div class="stage-card">
        <div class="stage-header">
          <div class="stage-num">1</div>
          <div>
            <div class="stage-title">USCIS Transfers Case to NVC</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stage-time-pill">2–6 weeks</div>
        </div>
        <div class="stage-body">
          <p>After USCIS approves your I-130, they physically mail (or electronically transfer) the file to NVC. USCIS will mail you an approval notice (I-797). Watch your CEAC portal at <a href="https://ceac.state.gov" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">ceac.state.gov</a> for the status to change from blank to "Case Initiated."</p>
          <ul>
            <li>You receive: I-797 Notice of Action (approval)</li>
            <li>NVC assigns: a case number (format: XXX2024000000) and invoice ID</li>
            <li>Action required: none yet — just monitor CEAC</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="stage-card">
        <div class="stage-header">
          <div class="stage-num">2</div>
          <div>
            <div class="stage-title">Fee Invoice Generation & Payment</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stage-time-pill">2–6 weeks</div>
        </div>
        <div class="stage-body">
          <p>NVC generates fee invoices in the CEAC portal. You must pay both fees before you can submit any documents.</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Immigrant Visa Application (DS-260) fee:</strong> $325 per applicant</li>
            <li><strong>Affidavit of Support (I-864) fee:</strong> $120 (CR-1 cases only)</li>
            <li>Payments accepted online via credit card or ACH bank transfer</li>
            <li>Status changes to "Paid" within 1–3 business days of payment</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="stage-card">
        <div class="stage-header">
          <div class="stage-num">3</div>
          <div>
            <div class="stage-title">Document Submission (DS-260 + Civil Docs)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stage-time-pill">2–6 weeks (your part)</div>
        </div>
        <div class="stage-body">
          <p>After fees are paid, you complete Form DS-260 online in CEAC and upload all required civil documents. This is the stage where most couples experience delays — completeness matters enormously.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Beneficiary: DS-260 (immigrant visa application), passport, photos, civil docs</li>
            <li>Petitioner: I-864 Affidavit of Support + supporting financial evidence</li>
            <li>Documents must be uploaded through CEAC as PDF or JPEG scans</li>
            <li>Translations required for any document not in English</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="stage-card">
        <div class="stage-header">
          <div class="stage-num">4</div>
          <div>
            <div class="stage-title">NVC Document Review</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stage-time-pill">4–12 weeks</div>
        </div>
        <div class="stage-body">
          <p>After you submit, NVC caseworkers review your package. This is NVC's internal processing time — you are waiting on them. The CEAC status stays "Documents Submitted" until they complete review.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>If complete: status moves to "Case Completed" → interview scheduling begins</li>
            <li>If incomplete: NVC sends a checklist (RFE) — you resubmit, then wait again</li>
            <li>Each RFE cycle can add 4–8 additional weeks</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="stage-card active">
        <div class="stage-header">
          <div class="stage-num">5</div>
          <div>
            <div class="stage-title">Case Completed → Interview Scheduled</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stage-time-pill">2–6 weeks</div>
        </div>
        <div class="stage-body">
          <p>Once NVC marks your case "Complete," they transfer it to the U.S. embassy or consulate in the beneficiary's country. The embassy then schedules the immigrant visa interview. You receive an interview appointment letter by email from the embassy — not from NVC.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Wait time depends heavily on the embassy's interview availability</li>
            <li>High-demand embassies (Manila, Mumbai, Mexico City) can add weeks to scheduling</li>
            <li>After interview: visa printed and mailed within 1–5 business days if approved</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2 id="ceac-status">CEAC Status Codes Explained</h2>
    <p>You can track your case at <a href="https://ceac.state.gov" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">ceac.state.gov</a>. Here's what each status means:</p>

    <div class="status-grid">
      <div class="status-card">
        <div class="status-name"><span class="status-dot dot-gray"></span>Case Initiated</div>
        <div class="status-desc">NVC received your approved petition from USCIS. Fee invoices not yet generated.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="status-card">
        <div class="status-name"><span class="status-dot dot-yellow"></span>Fees Invoiced</div>
        <div class="status-desc">NVC generated your fee invoices. Log in to CEAC and pay both fees to proceed.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="status-card">
        <div class="status-name"><span class="status-dot dot-yellow"></span>Fees Paid / Pending Review</div>
        <div class="status-desc">Payment confirmed. CEAC document upload portal is now open.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="status-card">
        <div class="status-name"><span class="status-dot dot-blue"></span>Documents Submitted</div>
        <div class="status-desc">You submitted your package. NVC caseworkers are reviewing. Typical wait: 4–12 weeks.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="status-card">
        <div class="status-name"><span class="status-dot dot-yellow"></span>Checklist Returned</div>
        <div class="status-desc">NVC found missing or incomplete items. Check your email for specific instructions and resubmit.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="status-card">
        <div class="status-name"><span class="status-dot dot-green"></span>Case Completed</div>
        <div class="status-desc">NVC accepted your package. Case transferred to embassy. Interview scheduling is next.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="status-card">
        <div class="status-name"><span class="status-dot dot-green"></span>Ready / In Transit</div>
        <div class="status-desc">Case en route to the embassy. You should receive an interview appointment notice soon.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="status-card">
        <div class="status-name"><span class="status-dot dot-red"></span>Administrative Processing</div>
        <div class="status-desc">After the interview, additional review required. Timeline unpredictable — can take weeks to months.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="cta-mid">
      <h3>Not sure what to submit at NVC?</h3>
      <p>The CR-1 visa checklist covers every document NVC requires — civil docs, financial evidence, police certificates, and translations.</p>
      <a href="/cr1-visa-checklist" class="cta-btn-blue">View CR-1 Document Checklist →</a>
      <a href="/affidavit-of-support" class="cta-btn-outline">Affidavit of Support Guide</a>
    </div>

    <h2 id="delays">What Causes NVC Delays — and How Bad Are They?</h2>

    <table class="delay-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Delay Cause</th>
          <th>Added Wait</th>
          <th>Impact</th>
          <th>How to Avoid</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Missing or expired civil document</td>
          <td>4–8 weeks per RFE</td>
          <td class="impact-high">High</td>
          <td>Use the full checklist before submitting</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Untranslated foreign-language documents</td>
          <td>4–6 weeks</td>
          <td class="impact-high">High</td>
          <td>Get certified translations before uploading</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>I-864 income below poverty guidelines</td>
          <td>4–12 weeks</td>
          <td class="impact-high">High</td>
          <td>Add a joint sponsor if income is insufficient</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Police certificate expired (most countries: 12 months)</td>
          <td>3–6 weeks</td>
          <td class="impact-high">High</td>
          <td>Time your police cert request to stay valid</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>DS-260 submitted with blank or "N/A" answers</td>
          <td>2–4 weeks</td>
          <td class="impact-med">Medium</td>
