    <h2 id="k1-vs-cr1-nvc">K-1 vs CR-1: Does K-1 Skip NVC?</h2>
    <p>Yes — the K-1 fiancé visa does not go through NVC at all. After USCIS approves the I-129F, the case goes directly to the U.S. embassy abroad, skipping the NVC stage entirely. This is one of the key structural differences between the two paths.</p>

    <div class="compare-box">
      <div class="compare-row header">
        <div class="compare-cell">Stage</div>
        <div class="compare-cell">K-1 Fiancé Visa</div>
        <div class="compare-cell">CR-1 Spousal Visa</div>
      </div>
      <div class="compare-row">
        <div class="compare-cell label">USCIS petition approval</div>
        <div class="compare-cell">I-129F: 10–16 months</div>
        <div class="compare-cell">I-130: 12–18 months</div>
      </div>
      <div class="compare-row">
        <div class="compare-cell label">NVC processing</div>
        <div class="compare-cell"><span class="badge-skip">Skipped ✓</span></div>
        <div class="compare-cell"><span class="badge-required">3–6 months</span></div>
      </div>
      <div class="compare-row">
        <div class="compare-cell label">Embassy interview</div>
        <div class="compare-cell">1–3 months</div>
        <div class="compare-cell">1–3 months</div>
      </div>
      <div class="compare-row">
        <div class="compare-cell label">Entry status</div>
        <div class="compare-cell">90-day K-1 visa (must marry + file AOS)</div>
        <div class="compare-cell">Enters as permanent resident</div>
      </div>
      <div class="compare-row">
        <div class="compare-cell label">Total estimated time</div>
        <div class="compare-cell">12–20 months</div>
        <div class="compare-cell">18–30 months</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>The NVC stage adds 3–6 months to the CR-1 path — but after entry, there's no Adjustment of Status required (unlike K-1). For couples who are already married, the CR-1 often makes more sense despite the longer timeline.</p>

    <h2 id="speed-up">6 Ways to Move Through NVC Faster</h2>
    <div class="tips-grid">
      <div class="tip-card">
        <div class="tip-num">Tip 01</div>
        <div class="tip-title">Submit a complete package the first time</div>
        <div class="tip-desc">Every checklist (RFE) adds 4–8 weeks. Use the official document checklist and triple-check before uploading. One missing police cert restarts the review clock.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="tip-card">
        <div class="tip-num">Tip 02</div>
        <div class="tip-num">Tip 02</div>
        <div class="tip-title">Get certified translations ready in advance</div>
        <div class="tip-desc">Professional translation takes 1–3 weeks. Don't wait until NVC opens the portal. Start translating civil documents as soon as USCIS approves your petition.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="tip-card">
        <div class="tip-num">Tip 03</div>
        <div class="tip-title">Pay fees the same day NVC invoices them</div>
        <div class="tip-desc">NVC can't open the document portal until fees are paid and confirmed (1–3 business days). Paying fast doesn't skip the queue, but it removes one controllable delay.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="tip-card">
        <div class="tip-num">Tip 04</div>
        <div class="tip-title">Time police certificates carefully</div>
        <div class="tip-desc">Police certificates are valid for 12 months in most countries (6 months for some). Request them close to your expected NVC submission date so they stay valid through the interview.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="tip-card">
        <div class="tip-num">Tip 05</div>
        <div class="tip-title">Use a joint sponsor if income is borderline</div>
        <div class="tip-desc">If your I-864 income is at or barely above the 125% poverty guideline, include a joint sponsor pre-emptively. A financial checklist RFE adds months — better to over-document upfront.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="tip-card">
        <div class="tip-num">Tip 06</div>
        <div class="tip-title">Monitor CEAC weekly — don't wait for emails</div>
        <div class="tip-desc">NVC emails can go to spam or arrive late. Check <a href="https://ceac.state.gov" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">ceac.state.gov</a> weekly. If your status hasn't changed in 12+ weeks after document submission, consider sending a polite inquiry to NVC.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2 id="contact-nvc">How to Contact NVC</h2>
    <p>NVC's primary contact methods:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Online inquiry:</strong> <a href="https://travel.state.gov/content/travel/en/us-visas/immigrate/nvc.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">travel.state.gov</a> → NVC Contact Form (preferred method)</li>
      <li><strong>Phone:</strong> 1-603-334-0700 (Monday–Friday, 7am–12am ET)</li>
      <li><strong>Email:</strong> <a href="mailto:NVCInquiry@state.gov">NVCInquiry@state.gov</a> (response time: 1–4 weeks)</li>
      <li><strong>CEAC portal:</strong> <a href="https://ceac.state.gov" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">ceac.state.gov</a> — check status 24/7</li>
    </ul>
    <p>NVC recommends waiting <strong>at least 90 days after document submission</strong> before inquiring about review status. Inquiries before that generally receive a form response with no new information.</p>

    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="faq-list">
      <div class="faq-item">
        <p class="faq-q">How long does NVC processing take in 2026?</p>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>NVC processing typically takes <strong>3–6 months</strong> from when NVC receives your approved petition to when they schedule your embassy interview. The exact time depends on how quickly you pay fees, how complete your documents are, and how busy NVC is at the time.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <p class="faq-q">Does the K-1 visa go through NVC?</p>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>No — the K-1 fiancé visa skips NVC entirely. After USCIS approves the I-129F petition, the case goes directly to the U.S. embassy in the beneficiary's country. Only immigrant visas (CR-1, IR-1, and family preference categories) go through NVC.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <p class="faq-q">What is "Case Completed" at NVC?</p>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>"Case Completed" means NVC has reviewed and accepted your entire document package and is transferring your case to the U.S. embassy for interview scheduling. This is one of the most important milestones — it means NVC's work is done and the embassy takes over.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <p class="faq-q">How long after "Case Completed" is the interview scheduled?</p>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>After NVC marks your case completed, interview scheduling at the embassy typically takes <strong>2–6 weeks</strong>. High-demand embassies (Manila, Mumbai, Mexico City, Lagos) can take longer — up to 2–3 months — due to high appointment demand.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <p class="faq-q">What happens if NVC sends a checklist (RFE)?</p>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>A checklist (sometimes called a "documentarily incomplete" notice) means NVC found missing, expired, or incorrect items. NVC will send you specific instructions by email. You correct the issue, re-upload through CEAC, and NVC restarts the review — adding 4–8 weeks per round. Submit complete documents the first time to avoid this.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <p class="faq-q">Can I check NVC processing times on a government website?</p>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>NVC does not publish real-time processing time estimates like USCIS does. You can check your individual case status at ceac.state.gov. Community forums like <em>VisaJourney.com</em> crowd-source actual timelines from real applicants — useful for understanding current real-world waits by country and visa type.</p></div>
      </div>
    </div>

